'''Tajon Trevor Buchanan''' (born February 8, 1999) is a Canadian professional [[Association football|soccer]] player who plays for {{Spanish football updater|Villarreal}} club [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] and the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada national team]]. Known for his speed and technical ability, he usually plays as a [[wide midfielder]], but can also be deployed as a [[Defender (association football)|full-back]].

==Club career==
===Early career===
Buchanan was born and raised in [[Brampton]], Ontario and is of Jamaican descent.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-02-22 |title=The Canadian National Football Team: When Football Meets Multiculturalism |url=https://breakingthelines.com/opinion/the-canadian-national-football-team-when-football-meets-multiculturalism/ |access-date=2026-05-04 |website=Breaking The Lines |language=en-GB}}</ref> His father died when Buchanan was seven years old.<ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/tajon-buchanan-became-canadas-fastest-rising-star/|title=How Tajon Buchanan became Canada's fastest-rising star|website=Sportsnet.ca|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> He began playing soccer with Brampton Youth, when he was eight.<ref>{{Canada Soccer player|id=13457|accessdate=2026-05-04}}</ref> Buchanan won the 2014 IMG Cup with the Mississauga Falcons.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tajon Buchanan - Men's Soccer |url=https://cuse.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=15560 |publisher=Syracuse University |accessdate=May 27, 2019}}</ref> At age 15, he moved with his best friend and his best friend's father (and his former coach), Chrys Chrysanthou, to Colorado where he joined the [[U.S. Soccer Development Academy|USSDA]] academy Real Colorado.<ref name="auto"/>

Buchanan spent two years playing [[College soccer in the United States|college soccer]] at [[Syracuse University]] between 2017 and 2018, making 33 appearances, scoring 12 goals and tallying six assists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tajon Buchanan - Men's Soccer - Syracuse University Athletics|url=https://cuse.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=13865|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> After two years with the Orange, Buchanan left early and signed a [[Generation Adidas]] contract with [[Major League Soccer]] ahead of the [[2019 MLS SuperDraft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/amaya-buchanan-to-headline-mls-generation-adidas-class/23ke1chi5oh81q0pqi2y4gi52|first=Ives|last=Galarcep|date=January 1, 2019|title=MLS SuperDraft: Amaya, Buchanan to headline MLS Generation adidas class|access-date=2026-05-04|website=www.goal.com}}</ref>

In summer 2018, Buchanan played for [[League1 Ontario]] side [[Sigma FC]], making seven appearances and scoring two goals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tajon Buchanan 2018 |url=https://www.league1ontario.com/roster_players/24798561 |publisher=League1 Ontario |accessdate=May 27, 2019 |archive-date=January 17, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210117154541/https://www.league1ontario.com/roster_players/24798561 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===New England Revolution===
On January 11, 2019, Buchanan was selected ninth overall in the [[2019 MLS SuperDraft]] by [[New England Revolution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boston.com/sports/soccer/2019/01/11/revolution-take-forwards-tajon-buchanan-dejuan-jones-in-mls-draft/|date=January 11, 2019|title=Revolution take forwards Tajon Buchanan, DeJuan Jones in MLS draft|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> He made his professional debut on March 9, 2019, as an 81st-minute substitute during a 2–0 loss to [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2019-03-09-new-england-revolution-vs-columbus-crew-sc/boxscore|date=March 9, 2019|title=Boxscore: New England Revolution vs. Columbus Crew SC 03/09/19|access-date=2026-05-04|website=Matchcenter}}{{Dead link|date=July 2025 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He scored his first career goal on September 12, 2020 in a 2-1 loss to the Philadelphia Union.<ref name="First MLS goal">{{cite web | title=10-man Revs drop heartbreaker in Philadelphia, fall 2-1 to Union | website=revolutionsoccer.net | date=13 September 2020 | url=https://www.revolutionsoccer.net/news/recap-10-man-revs-drop-heartbreaker-philadelphia-fall-2-1-union | access-date=23 September 2025}}</ref>

On November 24, 2020, he scored his first [[MLS Cup playoffs]] goal, scoring the second and final goal in a 2–0 win over the [[Philadelphia Union]].<ref>{{Cite web |last= |title=Recap {{!}} Revs advance to Eastern Conference Semifinals with 2-0 win over Union {{!}} New England Revolution |url=https://www.revolutionsoccer.net/news/recap-revs-advance-eastern-conference-semifinals-2-0-win-over-union |access-date=2026-05-04 |website=revolutionsoccer.net |language=en}}</ref>

On July 3, 2021 Buchanan scored the first goal in the history of [[Lower.com Field]], in the Revolution's 2-2 draw against [[Columbus Crew]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/597825 |title=Crew open new stadium with hard-fought draw against Revolution |accessdate=August 5, 2023 |date=July 3, 2021 |website=www.espn.com}}</ref>

During the [[2021 MLS season|2021 season]], Buchanan's continued good form for the Revolution earned him a nomination to the MLS squad for the [[2021 MLS All-Star Game]] in August 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/2021-mls-all-star-team-roster|date=August 4, 2021|title=2021 MLS All-Star Team Roster|access-date=2026-05-04|website=Mlssoccer}}</ref>

===Club Brugge===
In August 2021, Buchanan signed a three-and-a-half-year deal with [[Belgian First Division A]] champions [[Club Brugge]]. Buchanan was loaned back to New England Revolution for the remainder of the 2021 MLS season.<ref>{{cite web |date=August 24, 2021 |title=Tajon Buchanan to Club Brugge |url=https://www.clubbrugge.be/nl/nieuws/tajon-buchanan-naar-club-brugge |website=Club Brugge|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=August 24, 2021 |title=New England Revolution transfer Tajon Buchanan to Club Brugge |url=https://www.revolutionsoccer.net/news/new-england-revolution-transfer-tajon-buchanan-to-club-brugge |website=New England Revolution|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> The $7 million transfer fee (with a 10% sell-on clause) paid by Club Brugge was a club-record received by the Revolution for one of their players.<ref>{{cite web |author=Bogert, Tom |date=August 24, 2021 |title=Official: New England Revolution confirm Tajon Buchanan transfer to Club Brugge |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/sources-new-england-seal-club-record-deal-for-tajon-buchanan-to-join-club-brugge |accessdate=August 5, 2021 |website=www.mlssoccer.com}}</ref>

He made his debut for Brugge against [[Sint-Truidense V.V.|Sint-Truiden]] on January 15, 2022.<ref>{{cite web |last=Galindo |first=Peter |date=January 16, 2022 |title=Canadians Abroad Roundup: Buchanan, Corbeanu shining with new clubs |url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/article/canadians-abroad-roundup-buchanan-corbeanu-shining-new-clubs/ |work=[[Sportsnet]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> Buchanan scored his first goal for Brugge on April 24 against [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Bedakian |first=Armen |date=April 25, 2022 |title=WATCH: Tajon Buchanan scores 1st goal for Club Brugge |url=https://onesoccer.ca/a/watch-tajon-buchanan-scores-1st-goal-for-club-brugge |work=[[OneSoccer]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

===Inter Milan===
On January 5, 2024, Buchanan officially joined [[Serie A]] club [[Inter Milan]] for a reported fee of [[Euro|€]]7 million, plus €3 million in add-ons,<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Sessa |first=Francesco |date=January 5, 2024 |title=Adesso c'è anche l'annuncio, ufficiale Buchanan all'Inter: "È la scelta giusta, non vedo l'ora" |url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Calciomercato/Inter/05-01-2024/inter-buchanan-ufficiale-l-annuncio-dell-arrivo-del-difensore.shtml |access-date=January 6, 2024 |website= |publisher=[[La Gazzetta dello Sport]] |language=it-IT|trans-title=Now there is also the announcement, Buchanan is officially at Inter: "It is the right choice, I can't wait"}}</ref> signing a four-and-a-half-year deal with the Italian club.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1">{{cite web |date=5 January 2024 |title=Tajon Buchanan is a new Inter player |url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/tajon-buchanan-joins-inter |accessdate=5 January 2024 |website=www.inter.it/en |publisher=Inter Milan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Scianitti |first1=Matthew |date=4 January 2024 |title=Tajon Buchanan completes move to Inter Milan |url=https://www.tsn.ca/soccer/tajon-buchanan-completes-move-to-inter-milan-1.2057919 |accessdate=5 January 2024 |publisher=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]}}</ref> In the process, he became Serie A's first ever Canadian player.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" />

Buchanan made his debut for his new club on February 16, as a substitute for [[Alessandro Bastoni]] in a 4–0 victory over [[US Salernitana 1919|Salernitana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadiansoccerdaily.com/2024/02/16/canadas-tajon-buchanan-makes-inter-milan-debut-becomes-first-canmnt-star-to-play-in-serie-a/|first=Tom|last=Nightingale|date=February 16, 2024|title=Canada's Tajon Buchanan makes Inter Milan debut, becomes first CanMNT star to play in Serie A|work=Canadian Soccer Daily|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> On 10 May 2024, Buchanan scored his first goal for Inter, scoring the third goal in a 5–0 victory against [[Frosinone Calcio|Frosinone]], to become the first Canadian to score in Serie A.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadiansoccerdaily.com/2024/05/11/watch-tajon-buchanan-scores-first-goal-for-inter-milan/|first=Brendan|last=Dunlop|date=May 10, 2024|title=WATCH: CanMNT star Tajon Buchanan scores first goal for Inter Milan|work=Canadian Soccer Daily|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

=== Loan and move to Villarreal ===
On February 1, 2025, Buchanan joined [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] in Spain on loan with an option to buy.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Villarreal CF|url=https://villarrealcf.es/en/buchanan-ya-es-groguet/|title=Buchanan joins Villarreal CF|date=February 1, 2025|access-date=February 1, 2025}}</ref> On July 29, 2025, Buchanan made his move to Villarreal permanent, as Inter and Villarreal agreed on a fee of $14.4 million CAD, with the Serie A club receiving 20% of any future sale.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Scianitti |first=Matthew |date=2025-07-25 |title=Inter Milan, Villareal agree on transfer fee for Canadian Tajon Buchanan |url=https://www.tsn.ca/soccer/inter-milan-villareal-agree-on-transfer-fee-for-canadian-tajon-buchanan-1.2339055 |access-date=2025-07-25 |website=TSN}}</ref>

On August 24, 2025, Buchanan scored a [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]] in a 5–0 home win over [[Girona FC|Girona]], becoming the first Canadian to score a hat-trick in [[La Liga]] and the second Canadian to score one in [[Europe's top five leagues|Europe’s top five leagues]], after [[Jonathan David]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/la-liga/article/canadian-tajon-buchanan-records-hat-trick-with-villarreal-in-la-liga/|date=August 24, 2025|title= Canadian Tajon Buchanan records hat trick with Villarreal in La Liga |access-date=August 24, 2025 |website=sportsnet.ca}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Buchanan’s historic hat-trick makes LALIGA history – Web Oficial del Villarreal CF |url=https://villarrealcf.es/en/buchanans-historic-hat-trick-makes-laliga-history/ |access-date=2026-05-03 |website=villarrealcf.es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Staff |first=Canadian Soccer Daily |date=2025-08-24 |title=WATCH: Canada star Tajon Buchanan scores hat-trick as Villarreal destroy Girona |url=https://canadiansoccerdaily.com/2025/08/24/watch-canada-star-tajon-buchanan-scores-hat-trick-as-villarreal-destroy-girona/ |access-date=2026-05-03 |website=Canadian Soccer Daily |language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth===
Buchanan was named to the [[Canada men's national under-23 soccer team|Canadian U-23]] provisional roster for the [[2020 CONCACAF Men's Olympic Qualifying Championship]] on February 26, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Canada Soccer announces Provisional List for Concacaf Men's Olympic Qualifying |url=https://www.canadasoccer.com/canada-soccer-announces-provisional-list-for-concacaf-men-s-olympic-qualifying-p162594-preview-1 |publisher=Canada Soccer |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020 |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309191149/https://www.canadasoccer.com/canada-soccer-announces-provisional-list-for-concacaf-men-s-olympic-qualifying-p162594-preview-1 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A year later, he was named to the final squad for the rescheduled tournament on March 10, 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadasoccer.com/news/canada-soccer-announces-squad-for-concacaf-mens-olympic-qualifying/|title=CANADA SOCCER ANNOUNCES SQUAD FOR CONCACAF MEN'S OLYMPIC QUALIFYING|date=March 10, 2021|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

In Canada's opening match, Buchanan scored a brace in a 2–0 victory over [[El Salvador national under-23 football team|El Salvador]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://northerntribune.ca/canada-olympic-qualifying-el-salvador-2021/|first=John|last=Jacques|title=Buchanan Brace Leads Canada To Olympic Qualifying Opener Win|date=March 19, 2021|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> He was named the 2020 [[Canada Soccer Youth International Player of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/tajon-buchanan-jade-rose-named-canada-soccer-s-youth-players-of-the-year-1.1558688|title=Buchanan, Rose named Canada Soccer's youth players of the year|date=December 1, 2020|work=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

===Senior===

Buchanan accepted an invite for the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada senior national team]] camp for January 2021.<ref name="can2021">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/canada-soccer-ayo-akinola-national-team-camp-1.5853734|title=TFC's Ayo Akinola accepts invite to Canadian national team camp|date=December 23, 2020|first=Neil|last=Davidson|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> Buchanan was called up in June 2021 for the coming [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|World Cup qualification]] matches against [[Aruba national football team|Aruba]] and [[Suriname national football team|Suriname]], and subsequently made his senior-team debut against Aruba, setting up two goals in a 7–0 victory.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Canada beats Aruba, sets up crucial World Cup qualifier against Suriname |url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/article/canada-beats-aruba-sets-crucial-world-cup-qualifier-suriname/ |publisher=Sportsnet |accessdate=June 5, 2021}}</ref> On June 18, Buchanan was named to Canada's 60-man preliminary squad for the [[2021 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/canada-names-60-man-preliminary-roster-for-next-month-s-gold-cup-1.1656962|date=June 18, 2021|title=Davies, David highlight Canada's preliminary roster for Gold Cup|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

On July 1 he was called up to the final 23-man squad.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Canada Soccer announces 2021 Concacaf Gold Cup roster - Canada Soccer |url=https://canadasoccer.com/news/canada-soccer-announces-2021-concacaf-gold-cup-roster/ |access-date=2026-05-04 |language=en-CA}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the senior team on July 29 against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] in the semi-final stage of the Gold Cup, netting the equalizer in an eventual 2–1 defeat.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Canada impresses in 1:2 loss to Mexico in Concacaf Gold Cup Semifinal - Canada Soccer |url=https://canadasoccer.com/news/canada-impresses-in-12-loss-to-mexico-in-concacaf-gold-cup-semifinal/ |access-date=2026-05-04 |language=en-CA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Mario |first=Gavranović |date=2025-05-04 |title=kooralive |url=https://kooralive.website/ |access-date=2026-05-04 |language=en}}</ref> Buchanan's play at the tournament was widely praised by the region's media and at the conclusion of the competition he was named as the recipient of the 2021 CONCACAF Gold Cup Best Young Player Award.<ref>{{Cite web |last=mlssoccer |title=Revolution stars Turner, Buchanan earn major 2021 Gold Cup awards {{!}} MLSSoccer.com |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/revolution-stars-turner-buchanan-earn-major-2021-gold-cup-awards |access-date=2026-05-04 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref>

In November 2022, Buchanan was named to Canada's squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canpl.ca/article/canada-announces-26-man-squad-for-2022-fifa-world-cup-in-qatar|date=November 13, 2022|title=Canada announces 26-man squad for 2022 FIFA World Cup in Qatar|work=[[Canadian Premier League]]|first=Charlie|last=O'Connor-Clarke|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> In Canada's second match on November 27 against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]], the team scored their first ever goal at a men's World Cup, with Buchanan sending in a cross that was met by the head of [[Alphonso Davies]] and sent into the back of the net.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thebentmusket.com/2022/11/28/23481616/fifa-world-cup-2022-group-f-recaps-tajon-buchanan-canada-croatia-hakim-ziyech-morocco-belgium|date=November 27, 2022|title=FIFA World Cup 2022 Group F Recaps: Buchanan's historic assist not enough as Canada eliminated|work=The Bent Musket|first=Jake|last=Catanese|access-date=June 12, 2023|archive-date=December 2, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231202181015/https://www.thebentmusket.com/2022/11/28/23481616/fifa-world-cup-2022-group-f-recaps-tajon-buchanan-canada-croatia-hakim-ziyech-morocco-belgium|url-status=dead}}</ref>

In June 2023, Buchanan was named to the 23-man squad for Canada ahead of the [[2023 CONCACAF Nations League Finals]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Former CPLers Loturi, Zator called up by Canada for 2023 Concacaf Nations League Finals|date=June 7, 2023|url=https://canpl.ca/article/canada-canmnt-2023-concacaf-nations-league-final-roster|first=Mitchell|last=Tierney|work=[[Canadian Premier League]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> In June 2024, Buchanan was named to the Canadian squad for the [[2024 Copa América]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadasoccer.com/news/canmnt-announce-2024-copa-america-roster/|title=CANMNT ANNOUNCE 2024 COPA AMÉRICA ROSTER|date=June 15, 2024|work= [[Canadian Soccer Association]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> After Canada advanced to the knockout phase, Buchanan would suffer a broken tibia while training for the quarterfinal match against [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]], and would undergo surgery to repair the fracture.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/canada-s-tajon-buchanan-suffers-broken-tibia-will-have-surgery-on-wednesday-1.2143808|title=Canada's Buchanan suffers broken tibia, will have surgery on Wednesday|website=TSN|date=July 2, 2024|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

